page.text: This memo addresses parking requirements in Newton and their application at 135 Wells Avenue.
The first section compares Newton’s required parking ratio to current market demand, affordability
and tenure characteristics. The second section examines how proposed parking demand
management can effectively reduce necessary parking supply. The third section quantifies the
effects of these characteristics and strategies. This analysis concludes that Newton’s by right
requirement of 2.0 spaces per unit for this proposed project is not necessary and that the proposed
ratio is closer to what would be most appropriate (in fact, this analysis indicates the project could
operate effectively at an even lower ratio without burdening adjacent public and private parking
The final section compares Newton’s parking space design standards to those enforced by a variety
of other municipalities nationwide as well as to the actual geometric demands of a typical vehicle,
concluding the spaces proposed at 135 Wells Avenue are adequately sized.

text.i: Market demand: a trend toward fewer spaces per unit

page.text: While older multifamily developments in the Boston region built and maintain parking counts closer
to Newton’s required 2.0 per unit, a recent market analysis by Byrne McKinney, completed for the
proposed development, has observed that newer developments, in response to market trends and
new zoning approaches, tend to require and successfully utilize lower parking ratios. A survey of
recently permitted multifamily projects confirms this trend continues and verifies 1.25 to 1.50 parking
spaces per unit is the current market standard across the Boston region, even when transit access is
limited. In fact, while surveying older comparable developments with approximately 2.0 spaces per
unit, Byrne McKinney almost universally observed significantly underutilized parking facilities,
confirming that older parking requirements are excessive in today’s marketplace.
One explanation for this trend toward lower parking ratios is the parallel trend toward smaller renting
households and, as a result, smaller average unit typologies. Two decades ago, multifamily
developments were tilted toward two-bedroom unit typologies. Recent and permitted
developments include a higher proportion of one-bedroom and studio units. Households occupying
these smaller units are less likely to own multiple vehicles, necessitating fewer parking spaces per
unit. Indeed, proposed units at 135 Wells Avenue average 1.6 bedrooms each.
Another explanation for the trend toward lower parking ratios draws from broader demographic
and lifestyle trends among predominant rental market segments (i.e. 18-35 year old singles and
couples as well as older singles and couples in transient or downsizing circumstances). Due to the
rising cost of car ownership and the preference for walkable communities with strong transit
connections, these groups tend to own fewer cars per household. Stantec has observed this trend is
most pronounced in cities with strong knowledge sector economies such as Boston.
Increasingly, professionals (and particularly multifamily renters) are seeking shorter commutes with
less emphasis on driving. The Wells Avenue site introduces a unique opportunity for employees of
companies in the office park to live within walking distance of their jobs. It is likely that some
apartments will be rented by such local employees, reducing their need for access to personal
vehicles and, thus, parking spaces. This is supported by general trends Stantec has observed across
the country: improving an area’s jobs/housing balance reduces the need for parking spaces and
Verifying an effect Stantec has observed in many development circumstances across the country,
the Victoria Transport Policy Institute has found that affordable units demand at least 15-25% fewer
parking spaces than market rate units. The Institute has also found that excessive parking ratios have
a negative impact on housing affordability. The construction cost of parking impacts overall
development cost. The more parking constructed, the higher the overall development cost and, as
a result, the higher its average rents. To the extent tenant households use their share of parking, this
cost transference is justified. But, because they tend to own fewer cars than households of higher
incomes, lower-income households often end up paying for parking they don’t need.
According to Newton’s zoning code, all multifamily developments are subject to the same parking
requirement; no distinction is made between ownership and rental properties. According to the
2012 American Communities Survey, homeowners in the Boston-Cambridge-Quincy Metropolitan
Area own an average of 1.89 cars per household while renters own an average of 0.98 cars per
household. Focusing the analysis to multifamily housing, a Victoria Transport Policy Institute analysis
finds tenants in new multifamily rental developments demand 20-40% less parking than owners in
As part of a growing trend, developers and municipalities nationwide are approaching parking
capacity issues from the demand-side instead of the supply-side. Rather than tailor parking supply to
meet peak-period demand (and remain underutilized at all other times of the day and week),
parking demand can be managed so that the supply is more effectively utilized more of the time
(resulting in a smaller, more efficient parking supply). When coupled with expanded transportation
choices such as transit, biking, and walking, parking demand management strategies can both
significantly reduce how much new parking must be built and also help make better use of existing
parking. The Metropolitan Area Planning Council recently held a conference entitled “sPARKing
New Ideas: Parking Strategies for Stronger Communities” which convened public officials,
professionals, and academics around the development and promotion of these strategies in the
There is a wide range of parking demand management strategies and they can be combined to
amplify their effect. The following represent approaches and strategies to be employed at 135 Wells
Avenue that we feel justify a reduced parking requirement well below the 2.0 space/unit standard.
The next section of this memo will quantify the effects of these strategies on anticipated parking

text.i: Applying updated, flexible requirements that reflect market, affordability, and tenure characteristics

page.text: Unless a proponent seeks a special permit, Newton’s zoning ordinance requires a blanket approach
to parking supply minimums that does not reflect a variety of contemporary trends which point
toward the need for fewer spaces per unit in multifamily housing. Comparable rental properties
across the Boston region indicate the current market prefers smaller unit types than in decades past
and only demands 1.25 to 1.50 spaces per unit. Tenants in affordable housing units tend to own
fewer cars and typically demand 15-25% fewer spaces per unit than market-rate households.
Renting households also typically own fewer cars and typically demand 20-40% less parking than

text.i: Enhancing transit access to reduce the need for cars

page.text: We are in the midst of a new urban migration from the suburbs to the city. Increasingly, households
seek transit-oriented communities and housing options that reduce their reliance on cars. This is
particularly true among the market segments 135 Wells Avenue will likely attract (i.e. young
professionals and more transient older couples). This development will establish a “smart shuttle”
system that will provide quick and efficient access to the nearby MBTA Green Line, reducing
demand for parking spaces by 10-20%. As an added benefit, this shuttle could be made available
to Wells Avenue office tenants, reducing area traffic and parking demand at other properties by
diverting commuters from their cars to transit at rush hours.
Increasingly utilized across the country, “unbundled parking” separates the cost of a rental housing
unit from associated parking spaces. For example, rather than pay $1,500 per month for an
apartment that includes two parking spaces, a tenant could pay $1,100 per month for the
apartment and then $200 extra per month for each needed parking space. Practice and research
has found that giving consumers the choice to utilize more or less parking increases the likelihood
they will opt for fewer spaces to save money. In general, unbundled parking systems reduce vehicle
Byrne McKinney’s market analysis of comparable developments around the Boston region confirms
that unbundled parking is a common regional practice that the market has grown accustomed to.
In most cases, the study found the property included one space with the base rent and then
charged an extra fee for additional spaces. Based on this finding, 135 Wells Avenue will at least
partially unbundle parking cost from apartment cost.
Carsharing services such as Zipcar and Enterprise enable a large community of users to share the
use of a small set of cars. In urban core environments, carsharing can enable households that only
occasionally require a car to gain access to one when they need it. At 135 Wells Avenue, while a
carsharing option might replace the need to own any cars in some cases, it will more likely make it
easier for tenant households to realistically get by with only one car. Research finds renters aged 21-
39 (i.e. much of the target market for 135 Wells Ave) are particularly likely to participate in
carsharing, particularly when it is complemented by a strong transit connection such as the smart
shuttle proposed in this case. The developers have committed to at least one carsharing vehicle on
the property. A report issued by the Victoria Transport Policy Institute found that each carsharing
vehicle can supplant demand for 4-8 parking spaces.
Mixed-use environments present opportunities for complementary uses to share parking supply. For
example, peak demand for office parking (9am-5pm on weekdays) is nearly the perfect inverse of
peak demand for residential parking (evenings, overnight, and weekends). This inverse relationship
allows these uses to overlap their parking supply and reduce overall parking demand by around
The planned Workbar space at 135 Wells Avenue exemplifies this approach. Its peak parking
demand period will be during the workday, coinciding with the housing component’s lowest
demand period. Therefore, Workbar patrons will have access to more than enough parking to meet
Shared parking agreements and related contingency plans can also help manage parking overflow
events (so lots need not be sized specifically for these uncommon situations). While the developers
of 135 Wells Avenue plan to include enough parking supply to accommodate anticipated daily and
peak demand, they will make a commitment to plan for the management of overflow events
through on-street parking utilization and/or shared parking agreements with adjacent property
owner(s) to ensure residents and their guests do not negatively impact local private parking supply.

Newton’s off-street parking dimensional requirements are more generous than those required by
many major cities across the country. Newton requires 9’ wide, 19’ deep 90-degree off-street
parking spaces. As the table below demonstrates, many major cities and suburban communities
require spaces that are dimensionally similar to or smaller than those proposed at 135 Wells Avenue.
The City of Calgary funded a Bunt & Associates study to inform potential revisions to municipal
parking design standards based on the actual dimensions of today’s typical passenger vehicles. The
analysis surveyed the dimensions of 3,225 models of cars, SUVs, minivans, and pickup trucks typically
available in Calgary. The study concluded the ideal dimensions for a residential parking space are
8.2’ wide by 17.7’ deep. Because this study was skewed toward pickup trucks (the longest and
Alberta’s most popular vehicle type), it is safe to assume a depth closer to 16 or 17’ would
accommodate most vehicles in Newton (the study indicates that, while it is important to
accommodate 85-95% of available passenger vehicles, it is acceptable to stop short of comfortably
accommodating the market’s absolute largest trucks and SUVs).
Applying the Bunt & Associates study methodology here for illustrative purposes, consider a 2014
Chevrolet Tahoe SUV, one of the larger passenger vehicles on the market, which measures 16.8’
long and 6.7’ wide. To determine the necessary dimensions for a functional parking space, the Bunt
& Associates study recommends adding 22” width to accommodate an open passenger door and
6” depth for front bumper clearance. Thus, a Tahoe requires a parking space that is 17.3’ long and

This traffic assessment has been conducted in three stages. The first stage involved an
assessment of existing traffic conditions within the project area, including an inventory of
existing roadway geometry, observations of traffic flow, daily and peak period traffic counts,
and a review of traffic safety in the area.
The second stage of the study established the framework for evaluating the transportation
impacts of the proposed project. Specific travel demand forecasts for the project were
assessed along with future traffic demands on the study area roadways due to projected
background traffic growth and other proposed area development that may occur independent
of the proposed development. The year 2019 (a five-year time horizon) was selected as the
design year for analysis for the preparation of this traffic impact and access assessment,
consistent with state requirements. Analysis of area traffic operations in the year 2019 would
fully reflect the effects of the proposed development as well as background traffic independent
of the proposed development. The traffic analysis conducted in the second stage identified
both existing and projected future roadway capacities and demands.
The third and final stage of the study discusses possible measures to improve existing and
future traffic operations in the area.
Evaluation of the transportation impacts associated with the proposed project requires a thorough
understanding of the existing transportation system in the project study area. A complete inventory
and evaluation of the existing transportation system in the project study area was conducted. The
analysis of existing transportation conditions is based on the existing roadway network,
roadway/intersection geometry, traffic control, existing daily and peak hour traffic volumes, traffic
safety conditions, and existing public transportation. A description of existing conditions within

Wells Avenue, their typical home/work trips would be contained on Wells Avenue and would
not have any traffic impacts offsite. However, no traffic credit was taken for this scenario.
As shown by the change in traffic generation associated with the redevelopment project, the
introduction of a residential use within an office park has the benefit of changing the traffic
patterns associated with trips on this site. This is particularly important within an office park
where there is a single ingress and egress via Wells Avenue. Under existing conditions, the
traffic entering the Wells Avenue Office Park is particularly heavy entering the park in the
morning and exiting the park in the afternoon. While the overall traffic generation is fairly
similar for the redevelopment proposal, the entering traffic in the morning is reduced by
approximately 42 vehicle trips and the change in existing trips in the afternoon is limited to 14
new trips. The redistribution of traffic during the peak hours and non-peak hours is expected

The directional distribution of the traffic approaching and departing the site is a function of

SSD is the distance required for a vehicle approaching an intersection from either direction to
perceive, react and come to a complete stop before colliding with an object in the road, in this
case a vehicle exiting from a driveway. In this respect, SSD can be considered as the
minimum visibility criterion for the safe operation of an unsignalized intersection.
ISD, on the other hand, is based on the time required for perception, reaction and completion
of the desired critical exiting maneuver (typically, a left turn) once the driver on a minor street
approach (or a driveway) decides to execute the maneuver. Calculation for the critical ISD
includes the time to (1) turn left, and to clear the near half of the intersection without
conflicting with the vehicles approaching from the left; and (2) upon turning left, to accelerate
to the operating speed on the roadway without causing approaching vehicles on the main road
to unduly reduce their speed. In this context, ISD can be considered as a desirable visibility
criterion for the safe operation of an unsignalized intersection. Table 5 summarizes the sight

Measuring existing traffic volumes and projecting future traffic volumes quantifies traffic within
the study area. To assess quality of flow, roadway capacity analyses were conducted with respect
to existing conditions and projected No-Build and Build traffic volume conditions. Capacity
analyses provide an indication of how well the roadway facilities serve the traffic demands placed
on them. Calculated levels of service classify roadway operating conditions.
Level of service (LOS) is the term used to denote the different operating conditions that occur on a
given roadway segment under various traffic volume loads. It is a qualitative measure that
considers a number of factors including roadway geometry, speed, travel delay, freedom to
maneuver, and safety. Level of service provides an index to the operational qualities of a roadway
segment or an intersection. Level of service designations range from A to F, with LOS A
representing the best operating conditions and LOS F representing the worst operating conditions.
For unsignalized intersections, the analysis assumes that traffic on the mainline is not affected by
traffic on the side streets. The level of service is only determined for left-turns from the main street
and all movements from the minor street. The overall level of service designation is for the most
critical movement, which is most often the left-turn out of the side street. The evaluation criteria
used to analyze area intersections and roadways are based on the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual
It should be noted that the analytical methodologies typically used for the analysis of unsignalized
intersections use conservative analysis parameters such as high critical gaps. Actual field
observations indicate that drivers on minor streets generally accept smaller gaps in traffic than
those used in the analysis procedures and therefore experience less delay than reported by the
analysis software. The net effect of these procedural limitations of the analysis software is the
over-estimation of calculated delays at unsignalized intersections. Cautious judgment should
therefore be exercised when interpreting the capacity analysis results at unsignalized intersections.

As shown in Tables 6 and 7, minimal, if any, changes in levels-of-service are expected between
2014 Existing conditions and 2019 No-Build conditions. Similarly, minimal changes in operations
are expected between 2019 No-Build and Build conditions. Overall, a comparison of the No-Build

increases in delays at the study intersections. In fact, the minor decreases in traffic volumes during
the weekday morning peak hour resulting from the proposed change in use actually reduce delay
for certain movements and reduce vehicle queues slightly for certain movements.
As outlined above, the proposed redevelopment project is expected to have very minor
impacts on traffic conditions in the study area. In fact, the change in traffic flow created by
adding a residential use to the office park, which also houses commercial and non-profit uses,
is a benefit of the project. However, the Proponent proposes to assist the City of Newton with
area improvement initiatives related to the project, specifically, and for future growth of the
Wells Avenue area in general. The Proponent’s proposal to provide mitigation funding to the
City for capacity and other improvements at the intersection of Wells Avenue at Nahanton
Street are more fully described in the Proponent’s applications to the City.
The City of Newton, as part of its City-wide traffic signal inventory project, has identified
both short and long term improvements at this intersection. The short term improvements are
geared toward maximizing the efficiency of operations with the existing geometry, fixing
existing issues with the traffic signal equipment, and introducing pedestrian amenities
including an actuated pedestrian crossing of Nahanton Street. As part of this work, the City
has identified a cost of approximately $65,000 for these enhancements. In addition, long term
improvements have also been considered including traffic signal and geometric upgrades to
the intersection or potentially a roundabout in place of the traffic signal. Since this
intersection serves as the only entrance to Wells Avenue, the Proponent is proposing to assist
the City with its future improvement plans as described in their filings with the City.
The intersection of Nahanton Street and Winchester Street is currently an unsignalized T-type
intersection. This intersection has been a priority location for improvement by the City of
Newton for operational and safety enhancements. While the proposed development will not
have a negative effect on this intersection, the Proponent is willing to assist the City of
Newton with implementation of improvements at this location as described in the Proponent’s
filings with the City. The City has estimated the cost for these signalization improvements at
$175,000 . Figure 11 shows the proposed mitigation improvements to the intersection. As

An important initiative of the redevelopment project will be the introduction of a shuttle bus
service to the Wells Avenue park. The Proponent plans to contract with the 128 Business
Council, which operates shuttle buses in the area. The shuttle will connect the project to the
MBTA Green Line station at Newton Highlands Station, approximately two miles from the
site. The shuttle will be open to all residents who live in the proposed facility and other
business within the Wells Avenue office park, thereby reducing the dependence on private
automobiles for the existing site and surrounding businesses. The shuttle service is anticipated
to run for approximately 4 hours on weekday mornings and approximately 4 hours on
weekday afternoon to capture the commute to and from work. If there is demand for
additional service beyond that identified, the Proponent will consider expanding the hours and
days of operations. By providing a connection to transit, the implementation of the proposed

This study evaluated the impacts associated with the construction of 334 apartment units on a
acre site located at 135 Wells Avenue in Newton, Massachusetts. Primary access to the
site will be provided via a reconstructed driveway onto Wells Avenue. The site is currently
occupied by an active Boston Sports Club (BSC) operating from an approximately 62,000 sf
building. As part of this project, the BSC facility would be demolished.
The proposed development is projected to generate approximately 150 vpd on a typical
weekday. The corresponding new weekday morning and evening peak hour trip generation is
46 vph (-42 enter/88 exit) and 62 vph (48 enter/14 exit), respectively. The relatively low
traffic volumes projected to be generated by the proposed development will have minimal
effect on traffic operations within the study area. It should also be noted that in terms of
occupancy and traffic activity, the proposed residential use is complimentary to the office uses
along Wells Avenue. When the majority of the office traffic is entering Wells Avenue in the
morning, the residential traffic is exiting. Similarly, when the occupancy of the residential
building is at its peak late at night, the office buildings are essentially empty.
Detailed traffic analyses indicate that a majority of the study area intersections operate at
acceptable levels of service under existing conditions and will continue to operate at similar
levels in the 2019 No-Build and Build conditions. Although the proposed development is
projected to have minimal effect on area traffic operations, the proponent proposes to provide
